  "prompt": "In movies that play in the US, tires of cars are always squeaking. Why?",
  "response": "The squealing or squeaking sound of tires in movies is often exaggerated for dramatic effect. In reality, tire squeal occurs when the rubber of the tires slips against the road surface, usually during fast acceleration, sharp turns, or sudden braking. However, in many movies, especially action films or car chase scenes, this sound is amplified or added in post-production to enhance the sense of speed, tension, or excitement. The exaggerated tire squeal helps convey the intensity of a scene to the audience, making the car maneuvers more thrilling and dynamic, even if the actual driving might not produce such dramatic noises.",
